commitResults.messageTitle: fix: improve household and session management
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit includes several important fixes and improvements:

1. Fix duplicate household detection:
   - Add isSameHousehold method to properly identify duplicates
   - Fix EditHouseholdCommand to prevent creating duplicate households
   - Update HouseholdBook.hasHousehold to ignore same ID when checking duplicates

2. Enhance session management:
   - Combine note functionality into EditSessionCommand
   - Refactor SessionCard.handleSessionUpdate to use enhanced command
   - Support adding/updating notes directly when editing sessions

3. Update user documentation:
   - Reflect command changes in UserGuide.md
   - Reorganize command sections for better clarity
   - Update command examples and expected outputs

These changes improve data integrity by preventing duplicate households
and provide a more streamlined user experience for managing session notes.

commitResults.messageTitle: feat: enhance storage validation and add robust error handling
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit improves the application's resilience against invalid data:

1. Storage validation improvements:
   - Added data validation to StorageManager.readHouseholdBook()
   - Return empty Optional when JSON contains syntactically valid but
     semantically invalid household or session data
   - Implemented robust validation for household ID, name, address,
     contact, and session date/time formats
   - Fall back to sample data when corrupt/invalid data is detected

2. Data access enhancements:
   - Added getSessions() method to HouseholdBook and ReadOnlyHouseholdBook
   - Implemented collection of all sessions across households
   - Created unmodifiable list views to ensure data integrity

3. Test files:
   - Added comprehensive test JSON files for storage validation testing
   - Created test cases for invalid households, sessions, and mixed data
   - Added edge case tests for corrupted but valid JSON structure

These changes improve application stability by preventing invalid data
from being loaded into memory, while gracefully falling back to valid
defaults when necessary.

commitResults.messageTitle: refactor: replace Person references with Household throughout codebase
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit completes the transition from the AB3 template to our domain model:

- Removed all remaining Person references throughout the codebase
- Updated Messages.java format method to work with Household objects
- Adjusted formatting to include household ID and contact information
- Improved tag display with square bracket notation
- Removed email field which isn't used in our domain model

This change completes the migration from the AddressBook template to
our Em-Social application's domain model, ensuring consistent terminology
and removing unused code.

This commit adds a detailed UML component diagram that visualizes the
Em-Social application architecture:

- Created ArchitectureDiagram.puml using PlantUML

- Documented component interactions with directional arrows

This diagram provides a high-level overview of the system architecture,
making it easier for new developers to understand the application structure
and component relationships.

commitResults.messageTitle: docs: enhance user guide for better usability and clarity
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit significantly improves the User Guide to better serve our target users:

- Enhanced introduction section with clear identification of target users
- Added comprehensive assumptions about user knowledge and preferences
- Improved command documentation with clear parameter explanations
- Added warning messages for destructive actions with screenshots
- Included practical tips for effective product usage
- Created a detailed FAQ section addressing common questions
- Expanded glossary with domain-specific terminology
- Improved formatting for better readability and navigation
- Added hyperlinks to external resources and internal sections
- Updated command examples with realistic scenarios
- Distinguished required parameters from optional ones
- Added keyboard shortcuts and workflow optimization tips
- Ensured consistent language appropriate for social workers

These changes make the documentation more user-friendly, comprehensive,
and aligned with the needs of social workers using Em-Social.

commitResults.messageTitle: docs: simplify architecture diagram for better clarity
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit updates the architecture diagram to a cleaner, more minimal design:

The simplified diagram provides a clearer high-level overview of the

commitResults.messageTitle: Add storage tests for household book and sessions
commitResults.messageBody:
This commit adds comprehensive test coverage for the storage layer:

- Implemented JsonAdaptedSessionTest to validate session JSON conversion
- Created TypicalSessions utility class for test data
- Added JsonSerializableHouseholdBookTest to test serialization/deserialization
- Created test JSON files for various scenarios
- Enhanced JsonSerializableHouseholdBook to properly validate duplicates
- Added UUID constructor to Session for testing purposes

These tests ensure proper validation of household and session data during
storage operations, including handling of invalid data and duplicate entries.
fix edit session bugs and inconsistencies

commitResults.messageTitle: Enhance EditSessionCommand to use Household's session management
commitResults.messageBody:
Updated EditSessionCommand to leverage the Household class's built-in session
management capabilities:

- Now retrieves sessions through Household's getSessions() method which
  provides properly sorted sessions by date and time
- Improved validation of session indices against the actual household's session list
- Streamlined the process for updating session fields while preserving null handling
- Added proper conflict detection before committing changes
- Ensured clean removal of old sessions and addition of edited sessions

This change provides more robust session editing with better integration
with the existing household data model.
